<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1816,2023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,723,1888,1915]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">Eastern and worldwide Pacific distribution</emphasis>
. From the Bering Sea to Isla Santa Catalina, southern Gulf of California (
<bibRefCitation author="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E." box="[279,577,1924,1951]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" pagination="139 - 154" refId="ref9496" refString="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E. (2005) Cap. 12. Crustacea 4. Lophogastrida, Mysida, Amphipoda Tanaideacea &amp; Cumacea. In: Hendrickx, M. E., Brusca, R. C. &amp; Findley, L. T. (Eds.), A Distributional Checklist of the Macrofauna of the Gulf of California, Mexico. Part I. Invertebrates. [Listado y Distribucion de la Macrofauna del Golfo de California, Mexico, Parte I. Invertebrados]. Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum, Tucson, Arizona, pp. 139 - 154." type="book chapter" year="2005">Brusca &amp; Hendrickx 2005</bibRefCitation>
; García Madrigal 2007). Off SW Mexico (present study; 
<figureCitation box="[1216,1284,1925,1951]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1391,1416]" captionTargetBox="[303,1285,581,1335]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[268,1320,550,1366]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Localities where Scina nana Wagler, 1926, Scina pacifica (Bovallius, 1887), S. setigera Wagler, 1926, and S. submarginata Tattersall, 1906, were captured during this survey." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3909171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3909171/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). This widely distributed species (
<typeStatus box="[375,425,1961,1987]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">type</typeStatus>
locality off 
<collectingCountry box="[565,647,1961,1987]" name="Ireland" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">Ireland</collectingCountry>
, East Atlantic) occurs in the West Pacific, the Central Atlantic, and in the central part of the Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation author="Zeidler, W. &amp; De Broyer, C." box="[562,860,1997,2023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" pagination="1 - 104" refId="ref11384" refString="Zeidler, W. &amp; De Broyer, C. (2009) Vol. 3. Catalogue of the hyperiidean Amphipoda (Crustacea) of the Southern Ocean with distribution and ecological data. In: De Broyer, C. (Ed.), Synopsis of the Amphipoda of the Southern Ocean. Bulletin de l'Institut royal des Sciences naturelles de Belgique, 79 (1), pp. 1 - 104." type="journal article" year="2009">Zeidler &amp; de Broyer 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="336" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,152,287]" pageId="7" pageNumber="336">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,153,179]" pageId="7" pageNumber="336">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tattersall" authorityYear="1906" box="[324,550,152,179]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scinidae" genus="Scina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submarginata">
<emphasis box="[324,550,152,179]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="336">Scina submarginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to occur at depths between 200 and 
<quantity box="[1086,1175,153,179]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="336" unit="m" value="4000.0">4000 m</quantity>
. It is relatively easy to distinguish by features such as the distal extension of propodus in pereopod 1, but not in pereopod 2 (like in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bovallius" baseAuthorityYear="1885" class="Malacostraca" family="Scinidae" genus="Scina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="336" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="336">S. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the basis of pereopod 5 with long anterodistal projection. The sizes of the two examined females were 4.5 and 5.8 mm.
</paragraph>
